uest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallace","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Wallis  , especially in Scotland, where the name was introduced from the Welsh Marches by a family of tenants of the Stewarts in the 12th century.","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames, e.g.   Wallach  ."]},{"name":"Wales","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Wales near Sheffield (South Yorkshire). The placename means ‘The Welshmen’ and denoted a settlement of Brittonic speakers living on the boundary between the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of Northumbria and Mercia (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). See also   Wallis  .","habitational name from Wales, the country named from Old English <i>wēalas</i> ‘foreigners’ (especially those speaking Celtic or Romance languages). This meaning of the surname is quite rare."]},{"name":"Welsh","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Wallis had at least 7 daughters with John de Knovil. She died on 1 July 1246, in Uge, Tinglev, Sønderjylland, Denmark."},"et":{"–1 July 1246":"–1. juuli 1246","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1299–1368":"1299–1368","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1309–Female":"1309–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1316–1368":"1316–1368","–1246":"–1246","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1246":"1246","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1 July 1246":"1. juuli 1246","1309":"1309","1306":"1306","UK, UK":"Uge, Tinglev, Sønderjylland, Taani"},"fi":{"–1 July 1246":"–1. heinäkuuta 1246","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","1299–1368":"1299–1368","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1306–Female":"1306–Kuollut","1309–Female":"1309–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","1316–1368":"1316–1368","–1246":"–1246","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1246":"1246","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1 July 1246":"1. heinäkuuta 1246","1309":"1309","1306":"1306","UK, UK":"Uge, Tinglev, Sønderjylland, Tanska"},"fr":{"–1 July 1246":"–1 juillet 1246","1278–Male":"1278–Décédé","1299–1368":"1299–1368","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1306–Female":"1306–Décédée","1309–Female":"1309–Décédée","1312–Female":"1312–Décédée","1315–Female":"1315–Décédée","1316–1368":"1316–1368","–1246":"–1246","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1246":"1246","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1278":"1278",